        truth="Walk-in customers order pints and crowler fills at the taproom bar on a Square POS, while his dozen-odd wholesale accounts — neighborhood bars and two bottle shops — text or email keg orders that he scrawls onto a clipboard hanging by the office door. The core work is his alone: as head brewer on the 7-barrel system he runs 3-4 brew days a week, each a 10-11 hour haul from mash and boil through whirlpool to knockout, with every recipe and fermentation reading logged by hand on paper brew sheets clipped to each fermenter. Around those brew days he does daily cellar rounds — pulling gravity samples with a hydrometer, dry-hopping, crash-cooling, and kegging — and tracks the tank schedule on a wall whiteboard, later retyping some of the brew-sheet numbers into a Google Sheet. He self-distributes the finished kegs in his own van, dropping them at accounts around town. Invoices go out from QuickBooks, and he tallies production volumes off the paper brew sheets to file the monthly TTB federal excise report plus state excise, while the draft list gets updated on Untappd and reorder follow-ups with accounts are remembered rather than tracked.",
