        truth="Leads come in by word-of-mouth referral and his Facebook business page as calls and texts to his personal cell; he drives out for a free walkthrough, measures the space with a tape and a Bosch laser, scribbles dimensions and notes in a spiral notebook, and shoots reference photos on his iPhone. That night at the kitchen table he builds the estimate in an Excel spreadsheet by copy-pasting line items from old jobs and adjusting quantities, then texts or emails the client a PDF quote; a signed quote plus a deposit check is what kicks off scheduling and material ordering. The CORE work is the hands-on remodel itself — he juggles 2-3 jobs at once, each kitchen or bath running 3-5 weeks on site, and he personally does all the finish carpentry and tile: 8-10 hour days on his knees hand-cutting and setting tile, where a single bathroom floor-and-surround eats 2-3 full days of that work alone. He coordinates his plumbing and electrical subs by text, buys materials on his Home Depot Pro account and at the local lumberyard, and keeps a handwritten punch list he walks with the client at the final walkthrough. Billing is progress payments — deposit, a mid-job draw, and final — where a few invoices run through QuickBooks but most are handwritten, paid by check or Zelle, and warranty callbacks are remembered rather than logged.",
